</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/12890644-tara-mickela">Tara Mickela</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I&apos;m not usually the dissenter in the crowd, but as a middle school librarian I could think of one or two 8th grade advanced and mature readers who wou<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I'm not usually the dissenter in the crowd, but as a middle school librarian I could think of one or two 8th grade advanced and mature readers who would read this and talk about it with an adult, which I think would be very appropriate. Potential readers would be more abundant in high school, but discussion is key. The themes are mature and dark and confusing, but don't we want them to stretch their thinking and be confronted with bigger thoughts in a historical context and the ability to share their reactions with adults and peers?<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
